body:
When building CityCanvas, a social AR platform that lets users anchor 3D objects, text, and photos to GPS coordinates across a city, one of the earliest and most consequential architecture decisions was how to store, query, and render location-bound content at scale. This post walks through the two core technical challenges we faced: designing a geospatial content query system using Supabase and PostGIS, and bridging the gap between GPS coordinates and Three.js's Cartesian 3D world.

## The Core Problem: Location Data is Not Just Lat/Lng Pairs

When you first think about storing "content attached to a location," your mind might jump to a simple table with `latitude` and `longitude` columns. This works fine when you have a few hundred rows and your only query is "give me everything." But real-world AR content discovery doesn't work like that.

Consider what CityCanvas actually needs to answer at runtime:

- "What AR objects exist within 150 meters of where I'm standing right now?"
- "Return only content visible within my current camera frustum, which covers roughly a 60° arc in front of me."
- "Sort results by distance, but cap the result set so we're not trying to render 800 Three.js meshes simultaneously."

A naive lat/lng column approach requires you to pull a broad bounding box of rows, then filter in application code. As content density grows in popular areas—think a city center where hundreds of creators have dropped objects—this becomes a serious throughput problem. You're over-fetching, deserializing, and discarding data before any rendering even begins.

PostGIS solves this by treating location as a proper geometric type with spatial indexing built in. Supabase ships with PostGIS enabled, so you get this without managing a separate database infrastructure.

## Designing the Content Schema with PostGIS

The first step is storing content positions as actual geometry, not text columns.

```sql
-- Enable PostGIS if not already active
create extension if not exists postgis;

-- Content table for AR anchors
create table ar_content (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid references auth.users(id),
  content_type text check (content_type in ('3d_object', 'text', 'photo')),
  title text,
  payload jsonb,          -- stores model URL, text value, photo URL, etc.
  position geometry(Point, 4326) not null,  -- WGS84 lat/lng
  altitude_meters float default 0,          -- height above ground
  orientation jsonb,      -- quaternion for 3D rotation
  created_at timestamptz default now(),
  is_public boolean default true
);

-- Spatial index — this is what makes proximity queries fast
create index ar_content_position_idx
  on ar_content
  using gist(position);

-- Example: insert a 3D object anchored at Shibuya Crossing
insert into ar_content (user_id, content_type, title, payload, position, altitude_meters)
values (
  'some-user-uuid',
  '3d_object',
  'Cyberpunk Torii Gate',
  '{"model_url": "https://cdn.example.com/models/torii.glb", "scale": 1.5}',
  ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(139.7003, 35.6595), 4326),
  2.0
);
```

The `geometry(Point, 4326)` type stores the coordinate in WGS84, which is the same coordinate system GPS devices output. The GiST index on that column is what enables PostGIS to run spatial comparisons without full table scans.

Now, the proximity query from the client side:

```sql
-- Supabase RPC function: fetch AR content within radius
create or replace function get_nearby_content(
  user_lat float,
  user_lng float,
  radius_meters float default 200,
  result_limit int default 50
)
returns table (
  id uuid,
  content_type text,
  title text,
  payload jsonb,
  lat float,
  lng float,
  altitude_meters float,
  orientation jsonb,
  distance_meters float
)
language sql
stable
as $$
  select
    id,
    content_type,
    title,
    payload,
    ST_Y(position::geometry) as lat,
    ST_X(position::geometry) as lng,
    altitude_meters,
    orientation,
    ST_Distance(
      position::geography,
      ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(user_lng, user_lat), 4326)::geography
    ) as distance_meters
  from ar_content
  where
    is_public = true
    and ST_DWithin(
      position::geography,
      ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(user_lng, user_lat), 4326)::geography,
      radius_meters
    )
  order by distance_meters asc
  limit result_limit;
$$;
```

Two things worth noting here. First, we cast to `::geography` rather than `::geometry` when calling `ST_DWithin` and `ST_Distance`. The geography type treats Earth as a sphere and calculates true meter distances, whereas geometry uses flat-plane math. For a 200-meter radius query, the difference is small but real, and it eliminates a class of subtle bugs where objects appear in queries when they shouldn't. Second, the `result_limit` parameter is not just a convenience—it's a hard contract with the rendering layer. Three.js has real performance costs for each mesh in a scene; we decided early on that 50 simultaneously rendered objects was a reasonable ceiling for mid-range mobile devices.

Calling this from JavaScript with the Supabase client is straightforward:

```javascript
const { data: nearbyContent, error } = await supabase.rpc('get_nearby_content', {
  user_lat: currentPosition.lat,
  user_lng: currentPosition.lng,
  radius_meters: 150,
  result_limit: 50
});

if (error) {
  console.error('Spatial query failed:', error);
  return;
}

// Pass to rendering pipeline
renderARContent(nearbyContent);
```

This single RPC call replaces what would otherwise be a multi-step: fetch broad bounding box → filter in JS → sort → slice. The database does it in one indexed pass.

## The Coordinate Translation Problem: GPS to Three.js Space

Fetching the right content is only half the battle. Three.js operates in its own Cartesian coordinate system—typically with the origin at (0, 0, 0) and distances measured in scene units. GPS coordinates are in decimal degrees. You cannot simply pass `35.6595` as a Z-value to a `THREE.Vector3`. You need a translation layer.

The approach we settled on is local coordinate transformation: define the user's current position as the scene origin, then express all other content positions as offsets from that origin in meters.

The math relies on the fact that at small scales (sub-kilometer), you can approximate the Earth's surface as flat and use simple trigonometry to convert degree differences into meter offsets.

```javascript
// Convert WGS84 lat/lng to local scene coordinates
// Origin is the viewer's current GPS position
function gpsToScenePosition(contentLat, contentLng, contentAltitude, viewerLat, viewerLng) {
  const EARTH_RADIUS_M = 6371000;
  const DEG_TO_RAD = Math.PI / 180;

  // Latitude difference → north/south offset in meters
  const deltaLat = contentLat - viewerLat;
  const metersNorth = deltaLat * DEG_TO_RAD * EARTH_RADIUS_M;

  // Longitude difference → east/west offset in meters
  // Must account for latitude compression: longitude degrees shrink toward poles
  const deltaLng = contentLng - viewerLng;
  const metersEast = deltaLng * DEG_TO_RAD * EARTH_RADIUS_M * Math.cos(viewerLat * DEG_TO_RAD);

  // Three.js uses Y-up convention
  // X = east, Y = altitude, Z = -north (OpenGL convention: -Z is forward)
  return new THREE.Vector3(
    metersEast,
    contentAltitude,   // altitude above ground level
    -metersNorth
  );
}

// Usage: place fetched content into the Three.js scene
function renderARContent(contentItems) {
  const viewerPosition = getCurrentGPSPosition(); // from Geolocation API

  contentItems.forEach(item => {
    const scenePos = gpsToScenePosition(
      item.lat,
      item.lng,
      item.altitude_meters,
      viewerPosition.lat,
      viewerPosition.lng
    );

    // Load and place the 3D model
    if (item.content_type === '3d_object') {
      const loader = new THREE.GLTFLoader();
      loader.load(item.payload.model_url, (gltf) => {
        const mesh = gltf.scene;
        mesh.position.copy(scenePos);

        // Apply stored orientation if present
        if (item.orientation) {
          const q = item.orientation;
          mesh.quaternion.set(q.x, q.y, q.z, q.w);
        }

        // Apply scale from payload
        const scale = item.payload.scale || 1.0;
        mesh.scale.setScalar(scale);

        scene.add(mesh);
      });
    }
  });
}
```

The `Math.cos(viewerLat * DEG_TO_RAD)` factor in the longitude calculation is the part that trips people up. A degree of longitude represents fewer meters the closer you are to a pole because the meridians converge. At the equator, one degree of longitude is about 111 km. At Tokyo's latitude (~35.7°), it's about 90 km. Skipping this correction produces objects that are displaced westward or eastward by amounts that grow with the user's latitude.

This local-origin approach also keeps Three.js numbers small and well-behaved. If you tried to use raw GPS coordinates as scene coordinates, you'd be working with values like 35.6595 and 139.7003—numbers with very small differences (perhaps 0.0001 between two nearby objects). Floating-point precision loss at this scale would cause visible jitter in object positions, a well-documented problem called "floating point origin drift" in large-scale 3D environments. Using the viewer as the origin means your scene coordinates stay within a ±200m range, which is numerically clean.

## Handling Scene Refresh as the User Moves

One additional complexity: the user is walking. As they move, their GPS position changes, which means the local origin shifts, which means all existing scene objects need their positions recalculated. Doing this every second for 50 objects would be wasteful.

The approach we use is threshold-based refresh. We track the user's position continuously but only trigger a full scene repositioning when they've moved more than a configurable distance (we use 10 meters). For content discovery, we re-query PostGIS only when they've moved 30 meters from the last query origin—enough that new content might have entered or left the 150-meter radius.

```javascript
let lastQueryPosition = null;
let lastSceneOrigin = null;

const REQUERY_THRESHOLD_M = 30;
const REPOSITION_THRESHOLD_M = 10;

function onPositionUpdate(newPosition) {
  const distanceFromQueryOrigin = lastQueryPosition
    ? haversineDistance(newPosition, lastQueryPosition)
    : Infinity;

  const distanceFromSceneOrigin = lastSceneOrigin
    ? haversineDistance(newPosition, lastSceneOrigin)
    : Infinity;

  if (distanceFromQueryOrigin > REQUERY_THRESHOLD_M) {
    lastQueryPosition = newPosition;
    fetchAndRenderNearbyContent(newPosition); // full PostGIS query + scene rebuild
  } else if (distanceFromSceneOrigin > REPOSITION_THRESHOLD_M) {
    lastSceneOrigin = newPosition;
    repositionExistingObjects(newPosition); // recalculate positions only, no new fetch
  }
}
```

This two-tier update system keeps database load predictable while ensuring the scene stays geometrically accurate as the user walks.

## Why This Architecture Over Alternatives

We considered a few alternatives before landing here.

A tile-based system (like Mapbox's vector tiles) would chunk the world into fixed grid cells and pre-compute which content lives in each tile. This works well for static map features but poorly for user-generated content that's constantly being added, edited, and removed. Cache invalidation becomes a significant operational burden.

A purely client-side bounding-box pre-filter with in-memory sorting was prototyped first and worked acceptably at low content density. The problem was predictable: popular locations. In a hot zone with 500+ pieces of content, the client was receiving and deserializing everything within a 500-meter square just to discard 90% of it. PostGIS moves this work to the database where it belongs.

The decision to use Supabase's RPC mechanism rather than a PostgREST filter endpoint was driven by the need to encapsulate the `ST_DWithin` geography logic server-side. PostgREST's filter syntax doesn't expose PostGIS functions directly in a clean way; wrapping the query in a Postgres function gives us full SQL expressiveness and means the spatial logic lives in one version-controlled place, not scattered across client code.

---

Building CityCanvas required bridging several distinct technical worlds—geospatial databases, 3D rendering math, mobile GPS precision, and real-time content delivery—in a way that degrades gracefully on mid-range hardware. The PostGIS + Three.js coordinate bridge described here is the piece that holds it all together.

If you want a deeper dive into the Meshy AI text-to-3D integration, the PWA camera pipeline, or the Capacitor native layer setup, I've written more about CityCanvas's full architecture on my blog: https://mcw999.github.io/mcw999-hub/blog/city-canvas-guide/?utm_source=hashnode&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=city-canvas
